It has only two small pictures – of the Cabinet Office and of a couple outside a house to promote an energy scheme.

The site promised to save the public £50million by bringing together all Government departments in one place. It was described as ‘well thought out yet understated’ by the judging panel and – in a reference to fashion – ‘the Paul Smith of websites’ by museum director Deyan Sudjic.

‘Gov.uk looks elegant and subtly British thanks to a revised version of a classic typeface, designed by Margaret Calvert back in the 1960s,’ Mr Sudjic gushed.

The font used on the site is Gill Sans - the same as that used on Keep Calm And Carry On merchandise.

